SIMPLE: umbrage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Umbrage
<hw>Um"brage</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧m"br⟦asl⟧j; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ombrage</ets> shade, suspicion, umbrage, L. <ets>umbraticus</ets>
belonging to shade, fr. <ets>umbra</ets> a shade. Cf. <er>Umber</er>,
<er>Umbratic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Shade; shadow; obscurity;
hence, that which affords a shade, as a screen of trees or
foliage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where highest woods, impenetrable⟦br⟧
To star or sunlight, spread their <qex>umbrage</qex> broad.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Shadowy resemblance; shadow.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The opinion carries no show of truth nor <qex>umbrage</qex> of
reason on its side.</q> <rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The feeling of being overshadowed; jealousy of
another, as standing in one's light or way; hence, suspicion of injury
or wrong; offense; resentment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which gave <qex>umbrage</qex> to wiser than myself.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Persons who feel most <qex>umbrage</qex> from the overshadowing
aristocracy.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>umbrageous</ent>⟦br⟧
